%N A396077 T(n, k) is the least number of rolls that maximizes the probability the largest roll is k when sorting n elements using the bogosort algorithm where n >= 2, 0 <= k <= n-2.
%C A396077 If k = n-1 then the probability is 0 as it is impossible to roll k-1 since we cannot have exactly one element in the wrong place.
%C A396077 If k = n then T(n, k) is infinite. The larger the number of rolls the larger the probability to roll n in at least one roll.
%C A396077 Let p(n, k) be the probability of rolling k when bogosorting n elements. Let sp(n, k) = Sum_{i = 0..k}, p(n, i). Then T(n, k) is the value u that maximizes sp(n, k)^u - sp(n, k-1)^u in the positive integers.
%H A396077 David A. Corneth, <a href="/A396077/a396077.gp.txt">PARI program</a>
%F A396077 T(n, 0) = 1. Rolling more than once decreases the probability in all rolls all elements are in the wrong place.
%e A396077 T(6, 3) = 22. The probability of rolling at most 2 with 6 elements is sp(n, 2) = 265/720 + 264/720 + 135/720 = 664/720 = 83/90. sp(n, 3) = sp(n, 2) + p(n, 3) = 83/90 + 40/720 = 44/45. We now look for u such that (44/45)^u - (83/90)^u is maximal. This happens when u = 22.
